The North, Central American and Caribbean section of the [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification]] acted as the qualifiers for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]], to be held in Canada, Mexico, and the United States, for national teams which are members of the Confederation of North, Central American and Caribbean Association Football ([[CONCACAF]]). Three direct slots and two inter-confederation play-off slots in the final tournament were available for CONCACAF teams.

==Format==
On 9 May 2017, the [[FIFA Council]] approved the slot allocation for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]], which included six direct spots and two [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification (inter-confederation play-offs)|inter-confederation play-off]] spots for the CONCACAF region. However, in a change of format from previous World Cups, there would be no dedicated host country slot, with the slots of automatically qualifying host countries now taken from the quota of its confederation. If the tournament were to be co-hosted, the FIFA Council would decide which host countries would qualify automatically.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fifa.com/about-fifa/organisation/fifa-council/media-releases/fifa-council-prepares-congress-takes-key-decisions-for-the-future-of-t-2883353 |title=FIFA Council prepares Congress, takes key decisions for the future of the FIFA World Cup |publisher=[[FIFA]] |date=9 May 2017 |access-date=28 February 2023}}</ref> On 13 June 2018, three members of CONCACAF—[[Canadian Soccer Association|Canada]], [[Mexican Football Federation|Mexico]] and the [[United States Soccer Federation|United States]]—were selected as hosts for the 2026 World Cup by the [[68th FIFA Congress]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Graham |first=Bryan Armen |date=13 June 2018 |title=North America to host 2026 World Cup after winning vote over Morocco – as it happened |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/live/2018/jun/13/world-cup-2026-vote-fifa-nations-choose-between-north-america-and-morocco-live |website=The Guardian}}</ref>

On 14 February 2023, the FIFA Council awarded automatic berths for all three host countries, leaving three direct slots and two [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification (inter-confederation play-offs)|inter-confederation play-off]] slots to be decided through CONCACAF qualification.<ref name="automatic berths">{{cite news |url=https://www.fifa.com/about-fifa/organisation/fifa-council/media-releases/fifa-council-highlights-record-breaking-revenue-in-football |title=FIFA Council highlights record breaking revenue in football |publisher=[[FIFA]] |date=14 February 2023 |access-date=14 February 2023}}</ref> On 28 February, CONCACAF announced the qualifying format for 2026 World Cup qualification.<ref name="CONCACAF format">{{cite web |url=https://www.concacaf.com/news/concacaf-announces-formats-for-men-s-national-team-competitions-for-the-2023-2026-cycle/ |title=CONCACAF announces formats for men's national team competitions for the 2023–2026 cycle |publisher=[[CONCACAF]] |date=28 February 2023 |access-date=28 February 2023}}</ref>

*'''First round''': Four CONCACAF teams, ranked 29 to 32 based on the [[FIFA Men's World Ranking|FIFA rankings]] of December 2023, were divided into two matchups, played on a [[Two-legged tie|two-legged]] home-and-away basis. The two winners advanced to the second round.
*'''Second round''': Thirty teams, the two winners from the first round and CONCACAF teams ranked 1 to 28 based on the FIFA rankings of December 2023, were drawn into six groups of five teams. They played single [[round-robin tournament|round-robin]] matches (two home and two away), with group winners and runners-up advancing to the third round.
*'''Third round''': The twelve teams advancing from the second round were drawn into three groups of four teams. They played double round-robin home-and-away matches, with the three group winners qualifying for the World Cup. The two best-ranked runners-up advanced to the [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification (inter-confederation play-offs)|inter-confederation play-offs]].

==Entrants==
As [[Canada men's national soccer team|Canada]], [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]], and the [[United States men's national soccer team|United States]] were awarded automatic berths as co-hosts, they did not enter qualifying. All the remaining 32 [[FIFA]]-affiliated national teams from CONCACAF entered qualification. Based on the [[FIFA Men's World Ranking|FIFA rankings]] of December 2023, the top 28 teams received a bye to the second round, while the lowest four teams entered the first round.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://digitalhub.fifa.com/m/7bb71d129c0845f0/original/Draw-Procedures-for-the-Concacaf-Preliminary-Draw-for-the-FIFA-World-Cup-26_EN.pdf |title=Draw Procedures for the CONCACAF Preliminary Draw for the FIFA World Cup 26 |publisher=[[FIFA]] |date=23 January 2024 |access-date=29 January 2024}}</ref>

